<paragraph blockId="13.[140,1108,167,334]" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">
This species is known from northeastern 
<collectingRegion box="[601,692,167,193]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Arizona</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[704,764,167,193]" country="United States of America" name="Utah" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Utah</collectingRegion>
, northern 
<collectingRegion box="[883,1030,167,193]" country="United States of America" name="New Mexico" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">New Mexico</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion country="United States of America" name="Colorado" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Colorado</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[260,376,202,228]" country="United States of America" name="Wyoming" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">Wyoming</collectingRegion>
. It is characterized by a shiny, slightly more cordate pronotum than other members of the group, without notable basal punctuation, relatively flat elytral intervals, with small punctures in the elytral striae, and distinctive male genitalia. As first revisers, we choose 
<taxonomicName authority="Casey" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1918" box="[506,706,307,334]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sarpedon">
<emphasis box="[506,633,307,333]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="28">B. sarpedon</emphasis>
Casey
</taxonomicName>
as the valid name of this species.
</paragraph>
